There are a number of errors in your code, some trivial, some fundamental. The code below will work, and I&#39;ve added comments where I made changes:

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt; 
    #include &lt;string.h&gt; 
    
    int count_consonants(char str[]) {
        int count = 0;
        for (int i = 0; str[i] != &#39;\n&#39;; i++) { // You need &amp;&amp; in place of all || ...
            if (str[i] != &#39;a&#39; &amp;&amp; str[i] != &#39;e&#39; &amp;&amp;
                str[i] != &#39;i&#39; &amp;&amp; str[i] != &#39;o&#39; &amp;&amp;
                str[i] != &#39;u&#39; &amp;&amp; str[i] != &#39;A&#39; &amp;&amp;
                str[i] != &#39;E&#39; &amp;&amp; str[i] != &#39;I&#39; &amp;&amp;
                str[i] != &#39;O&#39; &amp;&amp; str[i] != &#39;U&#39; &amp;&amp;
                str[i] != &#39; &#39;) {
                count++;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
    
    int main() {
        char str[100]; // You&#39;ve missed the terminating ; here!
        while (str[0] != &#39;\n&#39;) {
            fgets(str, sizeof(str), stdin);
            if (str[0] == &#39;\n&#39;) break; // Jump out of the loop!
            printf(&quot;Number of consonants=%d\n&quot;, count_consonants(str));
        }
        return 0; // Always return an integer from main!
    }

Other than the two &#39;typo&#39; changes in the `main` function, you need to make a major change in the way you count consonants. In your original code, the `if` test will always be true, as only one of the `!=` comparisons can be false.

EDIT: Allow me to elaborate! Let&#39;s assume the first character in the test string is the letter `a` (a vowel, so we don&#39;t want to increment `count`). In the list of tests (where `i` will be `0`, so I&#39;ll use this index), according to **your code**, the first comparison: `str[0] != &#39;a&#39;` will give `false` (as expected); however, *all subsequent comparisons*, such as the second: `str[0] != &#39;e&#39;` will give `true` (because it isn&#39;t `e`, it&#39;s `a`), so the overall value of ***all*** tests will be: `false` OR `true` OR `true` OR `true` OR ...; thus, the `if` block will be entered and count will be incremented. This will be the same for any character: it can&#39;t be equal to all of your tests!

However, if you use the same tests but combine them with `&amp;&amp;`, the overall value of the tests will be `false` if **any one of the single tests is `false`**.

Feel free to ask for further explanation on how to concatenate `||` and `&amp;&amp;` comparison operators.

A far more concise implementation of `count_constants()` makes use of string/character handling functions provide by the `C` standard:

    int count_consonants(char str[]) {
        int count = 0;
        const char *UCconsonants = &quot;BCDFGHJKLMNPQRSTVWXYZ&quot;;
        for (int i = 0; str[i] != &#39;\n&#39;; i++) {
            if (strchr(UConsonants, toupper(str[i])) != NULL) ++count;
        }
        return count;
    }

