As the `events` function is triggered when the user clicks prev/next or switches views, you will need to get the events again by sending a request with the start/end filters, or if the Backend doesn&#39;t support it, you will have to make it on the client side.

I&#39;m not sure what is the relation between the `CalComponent` and the `SchedulerComponent` (Parent to child relation maybe?), but either they will need to communicate with each other using the EventEmitters or exporting the `getEvents` function into a service and call it wherever you want.

Example of the service solution:

In scheduler.component.ts

    events: (start: any, end: any, timezone: any, callback: any) =&gt; {
      this.myService.getEvents(start, end);
      callback(this.events);
    }


----------

In my.service.ts

    import { Injectable } from &#39;@angular/core&#39;;

    @Injectable({
      providedIn: &#39;root&#39;,
    })
    export class MyService{

      constructor() { }

      getEvents(start?: number, end?: number){
        var events: MyEvent[] = [];
        this.ipservice.getIP().subscribe(
        d =&gt; {
          this.ip = d;
          this.BookingService.getBookings(this.ip, start, end).subscribe(
            data =&gt; {
              this.bookings = data;
              this.bookings.forEach(booking =&gt; {
                events.push(this.bookingToEvent(booking));
              });
            }
          )
        });
        return events;
      }
    }

Don&#39;t forget to handle the `undefined` values for `start` and `end` in the `BookingService`

